SSIC 2020 Title: Growing of crops combined with animal production (mixed farming)
Detailed Definitions: This Sub-class includes the combined production of crops and animals without a specialised production of crops or animals. The size of the overall farming operation is not a determining factor. If either production of crops or animals in a given unit exceeds 66 percent of standard gross margins, the combined activity should not be included here, but allocated to crop or animal farming.
Cross References:
•mixed crop farming, see Group 011
•mixed animal farming, see Group 014

SSIC 2020 Title: Agricultural and animal husbandry service activities except veterinary activities
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes agricultural and animal husbandry services such as collection of agricultural and animal husbandry by-products (e.g. chicken feathers, palm leaves). The provision of agricultural equipment together with the services of drivers and other attendants of equipment is also covered in this Sub-class. 

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following activities:
•herd testing services
•poultry caponising
•coop cleaning
•sheep shearing
•preparation of crops for primary markets by cleaning, trimming, grading and/or disinfecting
•cotton ginning
•waxing of fruits
•sun-drying of fruits and/or vegetables 
•seed processing for propagation
Cross References:
•agricultural research and experimentation, see 72109
•veterinary activities, see 75000
•vaccination of animals, see 75000
•renting of agricultural equipment without driver or attendants, see 77399
•renting of animals (e.g. herds), see 77399
Group Title: AGRICULTURAL AND ANIMAL HUSBANDRY SERVICE ACTIVITIES EXCEPT VETERINARY ACTIVITIES
Class Title: Agricultural and Animal Husbandry Service Activities (except Veterinary Activities)

SSIC 2020 Title: Forestry, logging and related service activities
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the extraction, gathering and production of round wood for the forest-based manufacturing industries. Besides the production of timber, forestry activities result in products that undergo little processing, such as fire wood, charcoal, wood chips and round wood used in an unprocessed form (e.g. pit-props, pulpwood). These activities can be carried out in natural or planted forests. 

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•growing of standing timber: 
- planting
- replanting
- transplanting
- thinning
- conserving of forests and timber tracts 
•growing of pulpwood 
•operation of forest tree nurseries
•production of round wood
•gathering and production of fire wood
•production of charcoal in the forest (using traditional methods)
Cross References:
•sawmilling and planing of wood (including production of wood chips and particles), see 1610
•manufacture of pulp, paper and paperboard, see 17010
•production of charcoal through distillation of wood, see 20113
Division Title: FORESTRY, LOGGING AND RELATED SERVICE ACTIVITIES

SSIC 2020 Title: Stone quarrying
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes extraction of building and/or monumental stone from the earth.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•quarrying, rough trimming and/or sawing of monumental and/or building stone (e.g. marble, granite, sandstone, slate)
•quarrying, crushing and/or breaking of limestone
•mining of gypsum, anhydrite, chalk and/or uncalcined dolomite
•extraction and/or dredging of gravel
•breaking and/or crushing of stone and/or gravel
Cross References:
•quarrying of sand and clay, see 08102
•mining of chemical and fertiliser minerals, see 08900
•production of calcined dolomite, see 23940
•shaping, pulverising, grinding, and/or other treatment of stone and/or gravel not performed in conjunction with extraction or quarrying activities, see 2399
•cutting, shaping and finishing of stone outside quarries, see 23960
Group Title: QUARRYING OF STONE, SAND AND CLAY
Class Title: Quarrying of Stone, Sand and Clay

SSIC 2020 Title: Quarrying of sand and clay
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes:
•extraction of ceramic, refractory and/or other clay from the earth
•extraction of sand from the earth.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•extraction and/or dredging of industrial sand and/or sand from construction
•quarrying of sand
Cross References:

•mining of chemical and fertiliser minerals, see 08900

SSIC 2020 Title: Other mining and quarrying
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes mining and quarrying of other minerals, except for stone, sand and clay.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•mining of:
- metal ores
- thorium ores
- non-ferrous metal ores (e.g. aluminium (bauxite), copper, lead, zinc, tin, manganese)
- coal
- lignite
- chemicals 
- fertiliser minerals
•extraction of peat uranium and/or salt 
•mining and quarrying of various minerals and/or materials such as abrasive materials, asbestos and/or siliceous fossils meals
Cross References:

•extraction of crude petroleum and natural gas, see 09001

SSIC 2020 Title: Crude petroleum and natural gas production
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes extraction, exploration, dressing and/or beneficiating of crude petroleum and natural gas.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•extraction and/or exploration of crude petroleum oils, gaseous hydrocarbon (natural gas) and/or condensates 
•draining and/or separation of liquid hydrocarbon fractions
•gas desulphurisation
•extraction and/or exploration of bituminous or oil shale and/or tar sand
•production of crude petroleum from bituminous shale and/or sand
•processes to obtain crude oils such as decantation, desalting, dehydration and/or stabilisation
•mining of hydrocarbon liquid, obtained through liquefaction or pyrolysis
Cross References:
•service activities incidental to oil and gas extraction (excluding surveying and engineering design and consultancy services supporting mining, oil and gas extraction and offshore exploration activities), see 09002
•oil and gas field service activities such as directional drilling and redrilling; cementing oil and gas well casings, pumping wells and plugging and abandoning wells, see 09002
•manufacture of refined petroleum products (including recovery of liquefied petroleum gases in the refining of petroleum), see 1920
•manufacture of industrial gases, see 20111
•manufacture and repair of oil rigs, see 28241
•manufacture, repair and maintenance of oil rigs or equipment  for oil and gas extraction, see 28242
•operation of pipelines, see 49300
•geophysical surveying services, on a contract or fee basis, see 71119
•providing engineering design and consultancy services supporting mining, prospecting and offshore exploration services, see 71126
•providing manpower for the oil and gas industry, see 78102

SSIC 2020 Title: Processing and preserving of seafood
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes:

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•production of:
- fish, crustacean and/or mollusc products: cooked fish, fish fillets, roes, caviar, caviar substitutes, etc.
- fishmeal for human consumption or animal feed
- meals and/or solubles from fish and/or other aquatic animals unfit for human consumption
•preparation and/or preservation of fish, crustaceans and molluscs: freezing, deep-freezing, drying, smoking, salting, immersing in brine, canning, etc.
•processing of seaweed
•preparation and/or preservation of fish, crustaceans and/or molluscs through canning
Cross References:

•manufacture of:
- prepared frozen fish dishes, see 10750
- fish soups, see 10799

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture of cooked-food preparations (e.g. frozen dinners)

This Sub-class includes the manufacture of ready-made (i.e. prepared, seasoned and cooked) meals and/or dishes. These dishes are processed to preserve them, such as in frozen or canned form, and are usually packaged and labelled for re-sale, i.e. this class does not include the preparation of meals for immediate consumption, such as in restaurants. To be considered a dish, these foods have to contain at least two distinct main ingredients (except seasonings).

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in the manufacture of:
•meat or poultry dishes
•fish dishes, including fish and chips
•prepared dishes of vegetables
•canned stews and/or vacuum-prepared meals
•other prepared meals (such as "TV dinners")
•frozen or otherwise preserved pizza

This Sub-class includes all activities related to the manufacture of textiles or textile products, not specified elsewhere in Division 13 or 14, involving a large number of processes and a great variety of goods produced.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in the manufacture of:
•narrow woven fabrics, including fabrics consisting of warp without weft assembled by means of an adhesive
•labels, badges, etc.
•ornamental trimmings: braids, tassels, pompons, etc.
•felt
•tulles and/or other net fabrics, and of lace and embroidery, in the piece, in strips or in motifs
•fabrics impregnated, coated, covered or laminated with plastics
•metallised yarn or gimped yarn, rubber thread and/or cord covered with textile material, textile yarn or strip covered, impregnated, coated or sheathed with rubber or plastics
•tyre cord fabric of high-tenacity man-made yarn
•other treated or coated fabrics: tracing cloth, canvas prepared for use by painters, buckram and similar stiffened textile fabrics, fabrics coated with gum or amylaceous substances
•diverse textile articles: textile wicks, incandescent gas mantles and/or tubular gas mantle fabric, hose piping, transmission or conveyor belts or belting (whether or not reinforced with metal or other material), bolting cloth, straining cloth
•automotive trimmings
•pressure sensitive cloth-tape
•artists' canvas boards and/or tracing cloth
•shoe-lace, of textiles
•powder puffs and/or mitts
Cross References:
•knitted and crocheted fabrics, see 1430
•made-up textile articles such as curtains, pillow cases, napkins (except apparel), see 1392
•carpets and rugs, see 13930
•textile wadding and articles of wadding: sanitary towels, tampons, etc., see 17092
•transmission or conveyor belts of textile fabric, yarn or cord impregnated, coated, covered or laminated with rubber, where rubber is the chief constituent, see 2219
•plates or sheets of cellular rubber or plastic combined with textiles for reinforcing purposes only, see 2219, 2221
•cloth of woven metal wire, see 25999
Class Title: Manufacture of Other Textiles n.e.c.

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture of outer garments
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the manufacture of outer garments. The material used may be of any kind and may be coated, impregnated or rubberised.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in the manufacture of:
•wearing apparel made of leather or composition leather, including leather industrial work accessories such as welder's leather aprons
•work wear
•other outerwear or nightwear made of woven, knitted or crocheted fabric, non-woven etc for men, women and/or children: coats, suits, ensembles, jackets, trousers, skirts, shirts, T-shirts,pyjamas, nightdresses, dressing gowns, blouses, etc.
•babies' garments, tracksuits, ski suits
Cross References:
•manufacture of:
- brassieres and other undergarments, see 14102
- wearing apparel of fur skins (except headgear), see 14200
- knitted and crocheted apparel, see 1430
- footwear, see 15200
- wearing apparel of rubber or plastics not assembled by stitching but merely sealed together, see 2219, 2221
- leather sports gloves and sports headgear, see 32300
- safety headgear (except sports headgear), see 32909
- fire-resistant and protective safety clothing, see 32909

SSIC 2020 Title: Petroleum refineries
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes refining crude petroleum into refined petroleum products. Petroleum refining involves one or more of the following activities: 
•fractionation, 
•straight distillation of crude oil
•cracking
It also includes the manufacture of liquid or gaseous fuels or other products from crude petroleum, bituminous minerals or their fractionation products. 

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following: 
•production of:
- motor fuel: gasoline, kerosene, etc.
- fuel: light, medium and heavy fuel oil, refinery gases such as ethane, propane, butane etc
Cross References: •manufacture of biofuels, see 20298

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in blending or compounding refined petroleum to make lubricating oils and greases and/or re-refining used petroleum lubricating oils.
Division Title: MANUFACTURE OF COKE AND REFINED PETROLEUM PRODUCTS

SSIC 2020 Title: Iron and steel rolling mills
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes one of the following operations: 
•reduction of iron ore in blast furnaces and oxygen converters
•reduction of ferrous waste and scrap in electric arc furnaces 
•by direct reduction of iron ore without fusion to obtain crude steel. The crude steel is smelted and refined in a ladle furnace, and then poured and solidified in a continuous caster in order to produce semi-finished flat or long products. 

These products are used, after reheating, in rolling, drawing and extruding operations to manufacture finished products such as plate, sheet, strip, bars, rods, wire, tubes, pipes and hollow profiles.

Units in this Sub-class includes the manufacture of:
•hot-rolled and/or cold-rolled flat-rolled products of steel
•hot-rolled bars and/or rods of steel
•hot-rolled open sections of steel
•steel bars and/or solid sections of steel by cold drawing, grinding or turning
•open sections by progressive cold forming on a roll mill or folding on a press of flat-rolled products of steel
•wire of steel by cold drawing or stretching
•sheet piling of steel and/or welded open sections of steel
•railway track materials (unassembled rails) of steel
•seamless tubes, pipes and/or hollow profiles of steel, by hot rolling, hot extrusion or hot drawing, or by cold drawing or cold rolling
•welded tubes and/or pipes of steel, by cold or hot forming and/or welding, delivered as welded or further processed by cold drawing or cold rolling or manufactured by hot forming, welding and reducing
•tube fittings of steel, such as: flat flanges and/or flanges with forged collars, butt-welded fittings, threaded fittings, socket-welded fittings
•operation of blast furnaces, steel converters, rolling and/or finishing mills
•re-melting of scrap ingots of iron or steel
•pig iron and/or spiegeleisen in pigs, blocks or other primary forms
Group Title: MANUFACTURE OF BASIC IRON AND STEEL
Class Title: Manufacture of Basic Iron and Steel

•by direct reduction of iron ore without fusion to obtain crude steel. The crude steel is smelted and refined in a ladle furnace, and then poured and solidified in a continuous caster in order to produce semi-finished flat or long products. 

These products are used, after reheating, in rolling, drawing and extruding operations to manufacture finished products such as plate, sheet, strip, bars, rods, wire, tubes, pipes and hollow profiles.

Units in this Sub-class includes production of:  
•ferro-alloys

This Sub-class includes the pouring of molten iron and steel into moulds of a desired shape to make castings, i.e. the activities of iron and steel foundries.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in the manufacture of one or more of the following: 
•tubes, pipes and/or hollow profiles and/or of tube or pipe fittings of cast-iron
•seamless tubes and/or pipes of steel by centrifugal casting
•tube or pipe fittings of cast-steel 
•casting of: semi-finished iron products, grey iron castings, spheroidal graphite iron castings, malleable cast-iron products, semi-finished steel products, steel castings
Cross References: •manufacture of non-ferrous metal castings and further manufacturing them into finished products; these are classified based on the specific finished products

SSIC 2020 Title: Non-ferrous metal foundries

•semi-finished products of aluminium, magnesium, titanium, zinc, etc.

•heavy metal castings
•precious metal castings
•die-casting of non-ferrous metal castings

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•manufacture of machine tools for turning, drilling, milling, shaping, planing, boring, grinding, etc.
Cross References:
•manufacture of interchangeable tools for hand tools or machine tools:
- drills, punches, dies, taps, milling cutters, turning tools, saw blades, cutting knives, etc., see 2593
•manufacture of moulding boxes and moulds (except ingot moulds), see 25939
•manufacture of electrical hand-held soldering irons and soldering guns, see 27902
•manufacture of power-driven hand tools, see 28199
•manufacture of machinery for mining and quarrying, see 28242
•manufacture of machines for forming foundry moulds, see 28299
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Metal-Forming Machinery and Machine Tools

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of machinery and machine-tools - metal forming types (e.g. forging press, cold heading machines, press breaks)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the manufacture and/or repair of metal forming machinery and/or machine tools. 

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•manufacture of machine tools for working metals, including those using a laser beam, ultrasonic waves, plasma arc, magnetic pulse, etc.
•manufacture of stamping or pressing machine tools
•manufacture of punch presses, hydraulic presses, hydraulic brakes, drop hammers, forging machines, etc.
•manufacture of draw-benches, thread rollers or machines for working wires
Cross References:
•manufacture of interchangeable tools for hand tools or machine tools:
- drills, punches, dies, taps, milling cutters, turning tools, saw blades, cutting knives, etc., see 2593
•manufacture of moulding boxes and moulds (except ingot moulds), see 25939
•manufacture of electrical hand-held soldering irons and soldering guns, see 27902
•manufacture of power-driven hand tools, see 28199
•manufacture of machinery for mining and quarrying, see 28242
•manufacture of machines for forming foundry moulds, see 28299
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Metal-Forming Machinery and Machine Tools

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture of dies, moulds, tools, jigs and fixtures
Detailed Definitions: This Sub-class includes the manufacture and/or repair of special tools and/or fixtures, such as cutting dies and/or jigs. Units in this Sub-class are also known as tool and/or die shops.
Cross References:
•manufacture of interchangeable tools for hand tools or machine tools:
- drills, punches, dies, taps, milling cutters, turning tools, saw blades, cutting knives, etc., see 2593
•manufacture of moulding boxes and moulds (except ingot moulds), see 25939
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Metal-Forming Machinery and Machine Tools

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture of machine tool accessories (e.g. small cutting tools, precision measuring tools and other attachments such as tool holders)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the manufacture and/or repair of machine tool accessories and/or attachments for metal cutting and/or metal forming machine tools, for instance:
•knives and/or bits for metalworking lathes, planers, and/or shapers manufacturing
•measuring attachments (e.g., sine bars) for machine tool manufacturing
•metalworking drill bits manufacturing
Cross References:
•manufacture of interchangeable tools for hand tools or machine tools:
- drills, punches, dies, taps, milling cutters, turning tools, saw blades, cutting knives, etc., see 2593
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Metal-Forming Machinery and Machine Tools

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of metal additive manufacturing (AM) equipment (including metal powder)
Detailed Definitions: This Sub-class includes the manufacture and/or repair of metal additive manufacturing (AM) equipment, metal powder additive manufacturing (AM) equipment, three-dimensional (3D) printer (metal-forming) manufacturing equipment.
Cross References:
•manufacture of printers, see 26203
•manufacture of photocopy machines, etc., see 28171
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Metal-Forming Machinery and Machine Tools

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of metal-forming machinery and machine tools n.e.c. (including metalworking machinery)
Detailed Definitions: This Sub-class includes includes the manufacture and/or repair of metal-forming machinery and/or machine tools that are not elsewhere classified.
Cross References:
•manufacture of interchangeable tools for hand tools or machine tools:
- drills, punches, dies, taps, milling cutters, turning tools, saw blades, cutting knives, etc., see 2593
•manufacture of moulding boxes and moulds (except ingot moulds), see 25939
•manufacture of electrical hand-held soldering irons and soldering guns, see 27902
•manufacture of power-driven hand tools, see 28199
•manufacture of machinery for mining and quarrying, see 28242
•manufacture of machines for forming foundry moulds, see 28299
Examples of Activities Classified Under:
•machinery for metallurgy manufacturing
•machinery for metallurgy repair and maintenance
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Metal-Forming Machinery and Machine Tools

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of oil rigs
Detailed Definitions: This Sub-class includes the manufacture and/or repair of oil rigs.
Cross References:
•manufacturing offshore oil and gas well drilling and production floating platforms, see 30110
•manufacture of oil and gas field derricks, Christmas tree assemblies, rock drill bits, see 28242
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Machinery for Mining, Quarrying and Construction

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of other oilfield and gasfield machinery and equipment (e.g. derricks, tool joints)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes includes the manufacture and/or repair of other oilfield and/or gasfield machinery and/or equipment, such as:
•oilfield and/or gasfield derricks and/or tool joints
•continuous-action elevators and/or conveyors for underground use in oilfield and/or gasfield
•boring, cutting, sinking and/or tunnelling machinery (whether or not for underground use) in oilfield and/or gasfield
•machinery for treating minerals by screening, sorting, separating, washing, crushing, etc. in oilfield and/or gasfield
•earth-moving machinery (e.g. bulldozers, angle-dozers, graders, scrapers, levellers, mechanical shovels, shovel loaders) in oilfield and/or gasfield
•track-laying tractors and/or tractors used in oilfield and/or gasfield
Cross References:
•manufacture of oil rigs, see 28241
•manufacture of machine tools for metal cutting and/or metal forming, see 2822
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Machinery for Mining, Quarrying and Construction

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of construction machinery and parts
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes includes the manufacture and/or repair of machinery and/or parts for construction use, for instance:
•continuous-action elevators and/or conveyors for underground use in construction
•boring, cutting, sinking and/or tunnelling machinery (whether or not for underground use) for use in construction
•machinery for treating minerals by screening, sorting, separating, washing, crushing, etc. for use in construction
•concrete and/or mortar mixers for use in construction
•earth-moving machinery (e.g. bulldozers, angle-dozers, graders, scrapers, levellers, mechanical shovels, shovel loaders) for use in construction
•pile drivers and/or pile extractors, mortar spreaders, bitumen spreaders, concrete surfacing machinery etc for use in construction
•track-laying tractors and/or tractors used in construction
•bulldozer and/or angle-dozer blades for use in construction
•off-road dumping trucks for use in construction
Cross References:
•manufacture of lifting and handling equipment, see 2816
•manufacture of agricultural tractors, see 28210
•manufacture of machine tools for metal cutting and/or metal forming, see 2822
•manufacture of crane lorries, concrete-mixer lorries, see 29100
•manufacture of mining locomotives and mining rail cars, see 30200
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Machinery for Mining, Quarrying and Construction

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of machinery for mining, quarrying and construction n.e.c.
Detailed Definitions: This Sub-class includes the manufacture and/or repair of other machinery for mining, quarrying and/or construction not elsewhere classified.
Cross References:
•manufacture of lifting and handling equipment, see 2816
•manufacture of farm-type tractors, see 28210, 29100
•manufacture of machine tools for metal-cutting and/or metal-forming, see 2822
•manufacture of oil rigs, see 28241
•manufacture of oil and gas field derricks, Christmas tree assemblies, rock drill bits, see 28242
•manufacture of construction machinery, surface mining machinery, see 28243
•manufacture of crane lorries, concrete-mixer lorries, see 29100
•manufacture of mining locomotives and mining rail cars, see 30200
Examples of Activities Classified Under:
•boring machine manufacturing, except oilfield, gasfield and construction
•boring machine, repair and maintenance, except oilfield, gasfield and construction
•drilling and boring machine, manufacturing, except oilfield, gasfield and construction,
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Machinery for Mining, Quarrying and Construction

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of machinery for food products processing
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the manufacture, repair and/or maintenance of machinery for food products processing, for instance: 
•agricultural dryers
•cheese-making machines (e.g. homogenisers, moulders, presses)
•machinery for the grain milling industry e.g. machinery to clean, sort or grade seeds, grain or dried leguminous vegetables (winnowers, sieving belts, separators, grain brushing machines, etc.)
•machinery to produce flour and/or meal etc (grinding mills, feeders, sifters, bran cleaners, blenders, rice hullers, pea splitters)
•machinery for the bakery industry or for making macaroni, spaghetti or similar products (e.g. bakery ovens, dough mixers, dough-dividers, moulders, slicers, cake depositing machines)
•machines and/or equipment to process diverse foods e.g. machinery to make confectionery, cocoa or chocolate; to manufacture sugar; to process meat or poultry; to prepare fruit, nuts or vegetables; to prepare fish, shellfish or other seafood, machinery for filtering and/or purifying, other machinery for the industrial preparation or manufacture of food
•machinery for the extraction or preparation of animal or vegetable fats or oils
•machinery for the preparation of food in hotels and/or restaurants
Cross References:
•manufacture of food and milk irradiation equipment, see 26602
•manufacture of packing, wrapping and weighing machinery, see 28195
•manufacture of cleaning, sorting or grading machinery for eggs, fruit or other crops (except seeds, grains and dried leguminous vegetables), see 28210
•manufacture and repair of machinery for beverage production, see 28252
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Machinery for Food, Beverage and Tobacco Processing

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of machinery for beverage production
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the manufacture, repair and/or maintenance of machinery for beverage products processing, for instance: 
•machinery for the dairy industry e.g. cream separators
•milk processing machinery (e.g. homogenisers)
•milk converting machinery (e.g. butter chums, butter workers and/or moulding machines)
•presses, crushers etc used to make wine, cider, fruit juices, etc.
•machines and/or equipment to process diverse foods e.g. machinery for breweries
•other machinery for the industrial preparation or manufacture of drink
•machinery for the preparation of drinks in hotels and/or restaurants
Cross References:
•manufacture of food and milk irradiation equipment, see 26602
•manufacture of packing, wrapping and weighing machinery, see 28195
•manufacture and repair of machinery for food products processing, 28251
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Machinery for Food, Beverage and Tobacco Processing

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of machinery for tobacco processing
Detailed Definitions: This Sub-class includes the manufacture, repair and/or maintenance of machinery for the preparation of tobacco and/or for the making of cigarettes or cigars, or for pipe or chewing tobacco or snuff.
Cross References: •manufacture of packing, wrapping and weighing machinery, see 28195
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Machinery for Food, Beverage and Tobacco Processing

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of machinery for textile, apparel and leather production
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the manufacture, repair and/or maintenance of:
•textile machinery e.g. machines for preparing, producing, extruding, drawing, texturing or cutting man-made textile fibres, materials or yarns, machines for preparing textile fibres: cotton gins, bale breakers, garnetters, cotton spreaders, wool scourers, wool carbonisers, combs, carders, roving frames etc, spinning machines, machines for preparing textile yarns: reelers, warpers and/or related machines, weaving machines (looms), including hand looms, knitting machines, machines for making knotted net, tulle, lace, braid, etc. auxiliary machines or equipment for textile machinery (e.g. dobbies, jacquards, automatic stop motions, shuttle changing mechanisms, spindles and/or spindle flyers)
•textile printing machinery
•machinery for fabric processing (e.g. machinery for washing, bleaching, dyeing, dressing, finishing, coating or impregnating textile fabrics)
•machines for reeling, unreeling, folding, cutting or pinking textile fabrics
•laundry machinery (e.g. ironing machines, including fusing presses, commercial washing and/or drying machines, dry-cleaning machines)
•sewing machines, sewing machine heads and/or sewing machine needles (whether or not for household use)
•machines for producing or finishing felt or non-wovens
•leather machines (e.g. machinery for preparing, tanning or working hides, skins or leather, machinery for making or repairing footwear or other articles of hides, skins, leather or fur skins)
Cross References:
•manufacture of paper or paperboard cards for use on jacquard machines, see 1709
•manufacture of domestic washing and drying machines, see 27501
•manufacture of calendering machines, see 28199
•manufacture of machines used in bookbinding, see 28299
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Machinery for Textile, Apparel and Leather Production

Detailed Definitions: This Sub-class includes the manufacture of probe cards.

Detailed Definitions: This Sub-class includes the manufacture, repair and/or maintenance of semiconductor assembly and/or packaging machinery.

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of woodworking machinery
Detailed Definitions: This Sub-class includes the manufacture and/or repair of sawmill and/or woodworking machinery, such as circular and/or band sawing equipment, planing machinery, and/or sanding machinery.

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of polymer additive manufacturing (AM) equipment
Detailed Definitions: This Sub-class includes the manufacture and/or repair of polymer additive manufacturing (AM) equipment such as three-dimensional (3D) printer (plastic-forming) manufacturing.

•manufacture of photocopy machines, etc., see 28171

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of other special purpose machinery n.e.c. (including plating equipment, industrial paint mixers and chemical mixing equipment)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the manufacture and/or repair of other special-purpose machinery that are not elsewhere classified, for instance:
•machinery for making paper pulp
•paper and/or paperboard making machinery
•dryers for wood, paper pulp, paper or paperboard
•machinery producing articles of paper or paperboard
•industrial mixing equipment for chemicals and/or paints
•machinery for working soft rubber or for the manufacture of products of soft rubber (e.g. extruders, moulders, pneumatic tyre making or retreading machines and/or other machines for making a specific rubber product)
•printing and/or bookbinding machines and/or machines for activities supporting printing on a variety of materials 
•machinery for producing tiles, bricks, shaped ceramic pastes, pipes, graphite electrodes, blackboard chalk, foundry moulds, etc.
•diverse special-purpose machinery and/or equipment (e.g. machines to assemble electric or electronic lamps, tubes (valves) or bulbs, machines for production or hot-working of glass or glassware, glass fibre or yarn, machinery or apparatus for isotopic separation)
•tyre alignment and/or balancing equipment; balancing equipment (except wheel balancing)
•central greasing systems
•aircraft launching gear, aircraft carrier catapults and/or related equipment
•automatic bowling alley equipment (e.g. pin-setters)
•roundabouts, swings, shooting galleries and/or other fairground amusements
Cross References:
•manufacture of household appliances, see 2750
•manufacture of photocopy machines, etc., see 28171
Class Title: Manufacture and Repair of Other Special Purpose Machinery

SSIC 2020 Title: Installation of industrial machinery and equipment, mechanical engineering works
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the specialised installation of machinery. However, the installation of equipment that forms an integral part of buildings or similar structures, such as installation of escalators, electrical wiring, burglar alarm systems or air-conditioning systems, is classified as construction.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•installation of industrial machinery in industrial plant
•installation of industrial process control equipment
•installation of other industrial equipment (e.g. communications equipment, mainframe and/or similar computers, irradiation and/or electromedical equipment, etc.)
•dismantling large-scale machinery and/or equipment
•activities of millwrights
•machine rigging 
•installation of bowling alley equipment 
•mechanical engineering works
Cross References:
•installation of electrical wiring, see 43210
•installation of air-conditioning systems, see 43220
•installation of elevators, escalators, automated doors, vacuum cleaning systems, etc., see 4329
•installation of doors, staircases, shop fittings, furniture, etc., see 4330
•installation (setting-up) of personal computers, see 62090

Class Title: Installation of Industrial Machinery and Equipment

This Sub-class includes

- buses, trolley-buses and/or coaches
- motor vehicle engines
- chassis fitted with engines
- other motor vehicles (e.g. snowmobiles, golf carts, amphibious vehicles, fire engines, street sweepers, travelling libraries, armoured cars, concrete-mixer lorries, ATVs, go-carts and/or similar including race cars)
•factory rebuilding of motor vehicle engines
•factory retrofitting of engine onto motor vehicle

•manufacture of parts and accessories for motor vehicles, see 29300
•manufacture of tanks and other military fighting vehicles, see 30400
•maintenance, repair and alteration of motor vehicles, see 95301

•trailers and/or semi-trailers (e.g. for transport of goods: tankers, removal trailers; for transport of passengers: caravan trailers)

•outfitting of all types of motor vehicles, trailers and/or semi-trailers

•manufacture of parts and/or accessories of bodies for motor vehicles (e.g. safety belts, airbags, doors, bumpers)
•manufacture of car seats

SSIC 2020 Title: Building and repairing of ships, tankers and other ocean-going vessels (including conversion of ships into off-shore structures)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the building and/or repairing of ships, except vessels for sports or recreation, and/or the construction of floating structures such as floating cranes and/or drilling platforms.

This Sub-class also includes 
•manufacture of sections for ships and/or floating structures
•building and/or repairing of:
- commercial vessels:  passenger vessels, ferry boats, cargo ships, tankers, tugs, etc.
- warships
- fishing boats and/or fish-processing factory vessels
- hovercraft (except recreation-type hovercraft)
- ship parts 
•construction of:
- drilling platforms, floating or submersible
- floating structures (e.g. floating docks, pontoons, coffer-dams, floating landing stages, buoys, floating tanks, barges, floating cranes, non-recreational inflatable rafts)
Cross References:

- manufacture of iron or steel anchors, see 25999
- manufacture of marine engines, see 28112
•manufacture of navigational instruments, see 26511
•manufacture of lighting equipment for ships, see 27400
•manufacture of amphibious motor vehicles, see 29100
•manufacture of inflatable boats or rafts for recreation, see 30120
•ship-breaking, see 3830
•interior installation of boats, see 43309

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and repair of railway and tramway locomotives and rolling stock (including specialised parts except engines, electric motors and signalling equipment)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes manufacture and/or repair of:
•electric, diesel, steam and/or other rail locomotives
•self-propelled railway or tramway coaches, vans and/or trucks, maintenance or service vehicles
•railway or tramway rolling stock, not self-propelled (e.g. passenger coaches, goods vans, tank wagons, self-discharging vans and/or wagons, workshop vans, crane vans, tenders)
•specialised parts of railway or tramway locomotives or of rolling stock (e.g. bogies, axles and/or wheels, brakes and/or parts of brakes; hooks and/or coupling devices, buffers and/or buffer parts; shock absorbers; wagon and/or locomotive frames; bodies; corridor connections)
•mechanical and/or electromechanical signalling, safety and/or traffic control equipment for railways, tramways, inland waterways, roads, parking facilities, airfields, etc.

SSIC 2020 Title: Manufacture and assembly of bicycles, tricycles, trishaws and invalid carriages (including parts and accessories)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes manufacture of:

•invalid carriages with or without motor
•parts and/or accessories of invalid carriages
•baby carriages

•cabinets for sewing machines, televisions, etc.
•laboratory benches, stools and/or other laboratory seating, laboratory furniture (e.g. cabinets and/or tables)
•finishing such as upholstery of chairs and/or seats
•finishing of furniture such as spraying, painting, French polishing and/or upholstering
•decorative restaurant carts, such as dessert carts, food wagons

•ski-boots

SSIC 2020 Title: Transmission, distribution and sale of electricity
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the transmission and sale of electricity to households, industrial and commercial users. This economic activity may require a licence from the Energy Market Authority or its equivalent.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following: 
•operation of transmission systems that convey the electricity from the generation facility to the distribution system 
•operation of distribution systems (i.e. consisting of lines, poles, meters, and wiring) that convey electric power received from the generation facility or the transmission system to the final consumer 
•sale of electricity to the user, including through electric charging stations/kiosks
Cross References:
•generation of electricity by fossil fuels, see 35101

•other electricity-related services (e.g. electricity brokers, meter reading), see 35104

•provision of customer transfer services for electricity retailers and consumers

•purification of water for water supply purposes
•treatment of water for industrial or other purposes

SSIC 2020 Title: Operation of sewer systems (including sewer treatment facilities)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes:
•operation of sewer systems and/or sewer treatment facilities
•treatment of wastewater (e.g. human and/or industrial wastewater, water from swimming pools) by means of physical, chemical and/or biological processes like dilution, screening, filtering, sedimentation, etc.
•maintenance and/or cleaning of sewers and/or drains, including sewer rodding
Section Title: WATER SUPPLY; SEWERAGE, WASTE MANAGEMENT AND REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES
Class Title: Sewerage

SSIC 2020 Title: Collection of waste
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes: 
•collection of non-hazardous solid waste (i.e. garbage) within a local area, such as collection of waste (including mixed recoverable materials) from households and businesses by various means (e.g. refuse bins, wheeled bins, containers) 
•collection of hazardous or toxic waste like:
- used oil from shipment or garages
- bio-hazardous waste
- used batteries
•collection of recyclable materials 
•collection of used cooking oils and/or fats
•collection of refuse in litter-bins in public places
•operation of waste transfer stations for hazardous and/or non-hazardous waste
•collection of construction and demolition waste
•collection and removal of debris
Cross References:
•remediation activities like decontamination of soils and groundwater at the place of pollution, after accidental pollution, etc., see 38200
•operation of landfills for the disposal of waste, see 38200
•operation of facilities where commingled recoverable materials such as paper, plastics are sorted into distinct categories, see 3830
Section Title: WATER SUPPLY; SEWERAGE, WASTE MANAGEMENT AND REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES
Division Title: WASTE COLLECTION, TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL ACTIVITIES; MATERIALS RECOVERY
Class Title: Collection of Waste

SSIC 2020 Title: Treatment and disposal of waste (including remediation activities)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the treatment prior to disposal and other treatment of hazardous and non-hazardous waste, the disposal of waste, and remediation activities. The waste may be in solid or non-solid form. 

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•operation of landfills for disposal of waste
•disposal of waste by combustion or incineration or other methods, with or without the resulting production of electricity or steam, substitute fuels, biogas, ashes or other by-products for further use, etc.
•treatment of organic waste for disposal
•disposal of used goods such as refrigerators to eliminate harmful waste
•remediation activities like:
- decontamination of soils and groundwater at the place of pollution, either in situ or ex situ
- decontamination and cleaning up of surface water following accidental pollution
- cleaning up of oil spills and other pollutions on land, in surface water, in ocean and seas, including coastal areas and other specialised pollution-control activities
Section Title: WATER SUPPLY; SEWERAGE, WASTE MANAGEMENT AND REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES
Division Title: WASTE COLLECTION, TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL ACTIVITIES; MATERIALS RECOVERY

SSIC 2020 Title: Recycling of metal waste and scrap
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes recycling of metal waste and scrap.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following: 
•processing of metal waste and scrap into secondary raw materials, or a form which is readily transformed into new raw materials. This usually requires a mechanical or chemical transformation process.
•separating and sorting of recoverable metal waste and scrap from garbage
•separating and sorting of commingled recoverable metal waste and scrap into distinct categories like used aluminium beverage cans and metals
Cross References:
•manufacture of new final products from (whether or not self-produced) secondary metal raw materials, such as spinning yarn from garnetted stock, making pulp from paper waste, retreading tyres or production of metal from metal scrap, see corresponding classes in Section C (Manufacturing)
•remelting ferrous waste and scrap, see 24102
•treatment and disposal of waste, see 38200
•treatment of organic waste for disposal, see 38200
•energy recovery from non-hazardous waste incineration processes, see 38200
•recycling of non-metal waste, see 38309
•disposal of used goods such as refrigerators to eliminate harmful waste, see 38200
•treatment and disposal of toxic, contaminated waste, see 38200
•wholesale of other intermediate products, waste and scrap, see 4665
•dismantling of automobiles, computers, televisions and other equipment to obtain and re-sell usable parts, see Section G (Wholesale and Retail)

SSIC 2020 Title: General contractors (building construction including major upgrading works)

- non-landed buildings, like high-rise public housing and/or condominiums
- construction of all types of commercial buildings, like office buildings, shophouses, shopping malls, indoor sports facilities, carparks and/or hotels
- construction of buildings for production, like factories, workshops, assembly plants and/or warehouses
- construction of institutional and other buildings, such as healthcare, educational and religious facilities
•major additions and alterations or upgrading to existing building structures

•production of precast concrete, wood or steel components such as:
- beams, columns, planks, hollowcore slab, rafters and/or roof struts
- load bearing walls, household shelters, prefabricated bathroom units, facades
- bay windows, staircases, non-load bearing walls/panels, planter boxes
- refuse chutes, tunnel segments, drains and kerbs
- glue-laminated or metal connected prefabricated roof trusses
- parquet floor blocks, strips, etc., assembled into panels
- railings, doors, windows, shutters and/or their frames
•production of pre-fabricated buildings, or elements thereof, predominantly of metal, wood or concrete (e.g. site huts, modular exhibition elements)
•production of mobile homes

Installation and erection may/may not be carried out by establishment itself
Cross References:
•foundation works (including micropiling, conventional piling and underpinning), see 43901
•brick laying, stone setting and cement works, see 43902
•roofing works (including timber carcassing), see 43903
•scaffolding works, see 43905
•sandblasting/shotblasting works (except ships), see 43906
Class Title: Other Specialised Construction Activities

Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes activities of commission agents and all other wholesalers who trade goods on behalf and/or on account of others. Such agents and wholesalers do not take title to the goods they sell, but act as agents for a principal and receive a commission or fee for their service.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•activities of those involved in bringing sellers and buyers together or undertaking commercial transactions on behalf of a principal, excluding via the Internet
•activities of wholesale auctioneering houses

•arranging or organising of transport operations by rail, road, sea or air
•organisation of group and individual consignments (including pickup and delivery of goods and grouping of consignments)
•activities of sea-freight forwarders and air-cargo agents
•goods-handling operations, e.g. temporary crating for the sole purpose of protecting the goods during transit, uncrating, sampling and/or weighing of goods
•issue and procurement of transport documents and/or waybills
•activities of customs agents
Cross References:
•courier activities, see 53200
•provision of motor, marine, aviation and transport insurance, see 6512
•activities of travel agencies and tour operators, see 7910
Division Title: WAREHOUSING AND SUPPORT ACTIVITIES FOR TRANSPORTATION
Class Title: Other Transportation Support Activities

SSIC 2020 Title: National post activities (e.g. postal services)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the activities of postal services operating involving the conveyance of letters and/or postal articles through the postal service infrastructure. This economic activity may require a Postal Services Operator’s licence that is issued by the Info-communications Media Development Authority or its equivalent.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•receiving, collecting, sorting, sending, despatching and delivering (domestic and international) of postal articles (i.e. letter-post and parcel-post) and any other related services 
- items delivered can include letters, postcards, printed papers (newspaper, periodicals, advertising items, etc.), small packets, goods or documents of up to 2kg only. 
- one or more modes of transport may be involved and the activity may be carried out with either self-owned (private) transport or via public transport
•collection of postal articles from the postal network, such as public letter-boxes or from post offices
•distribution and delivery of postal articles
Cross References: •courier activities not operating under a universal service obligation, see 53200
Class Title: National Post Activities

SSIC 2020 Title: Courier activities other than national post activities
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes courier activities involving the conveyance of express letters and parcel items, and general commercial items. Courier activities (other than national post activities) involves the conveyance of express letters or items through networks other than the postal service infrastructure, and typically involve value-added services such as door-to-door pick-up and delivery of items, item tracking and acknowledgement of receipt of the item. One or more modes of transport may be involved and the activity may be carried out with either self-owned (private) transport or via public transport.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•pickup, sorting, transport and delivery (domestic or international) of letters and parcels by firms not utilising the postal service infrastructure
•distribution and delivery of mail and parcels
Cross References:
•transport of freight (according to mode of transport), see 4910, 4923, 5002, 510
•national post activities (e.g. postal services), see 53100
Class Title: Courier Activities Other than National Post Activities

SSIC 2020 Title: Hotels
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes:
•the provision of furnished accommodation in hotels, typically on a daily or weekly basis, principally for short stay by visitors
•Examples of facilities and/or services provided:
- daily or other regular housekeeping services
- food and beverage services in restaurants on the premises
- laundry services
- swimming pools and/or exercise rooms
- conference and/or convention facilities
•provision of hotel management services (i.e. providing management and operating staff to run hotel)
Cross References:
•chalets, see 55102
•hostels or guesthouses, see 55103
•online marketplaces for travel services, see 63204
•online intermediaries that enable transactions between buyers and sellers usually for a fee or commission basis without providing the travel services sold, see 63204
•provision of homes and furnished or unfurnished flats or apartments for more permanent use, typically on a monthly or annual basis, see 68102
•overseeing and managing related enterprises, such as undertaking the strategic planning, decision making and operational control of these related enterprises, see 70101
•provision of a range of centralised administrative services (e.g. marketing, recruitment, finance) to related enterprises, see 70101
•provision of consultancy services for hotels on management, see 70203
•combination of day-to-day administrative services to non-related enterprises, see 82110
Class Title: Short Term Accommodation Activities

SSIC 2020 Title: Chalets
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes:
•the provision of accommodation, typically on a daily or weekly basis, principally for short stay by visitors, in self-contained space consisting of complete furnished rooms or areas for living/dining and sleeping, with cooking facilities or fully equipped kitchens. This may take the form of clusters of buildings or single storey bungalows and chalets. Very minimal complementary services, if any, are provided.
•provision of chalet management services (i.e. providing management and operating staff to run chalets).
Cross References:
•hotels, see 55101
•hostels or guesthouses, see 55103
•online marketplaces for travel services, see 63204
•online intermediaries that enable transactions between buyers and sellers usually for a fee or commission basis without providing the travel services sold, see 63204
•provision of homes and furnished or unfurnished flats or apartments for more permanent use, typically on a monthly or annual basis, see 68102
•overseeing and managing related enterprises, such as undertaking the strategic planning, decision making and operational control of these related enterprises, see 70101
•combination of day-to-day administrative services to non-related enterprises, see 82110
Class Title: Short Term Accommodation Activities

SSIC 2020 Title: Short term accommodation activities other than hotels and chalets
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes:
•the provision of furnished accommodation in facilities known as hostels or guesthouses, typically on a daily or weekly basis, principally for short stay by visitors. Daily or other regular housekeeping services might be provided
•provision of hostels or guesthouse accommodation management services (i.e. providing management and operating staff to run short term accommodation like hostels or guesthouses)
Cross References:
•hotels, see 55101
•chalets, see 55102
•hostels and dormitories for students, workers and other individuals, see 55900
•online marketplaces for travel services, see 63204
•online intermediaries that enable transactions between buyers and sellers usually for a fee or commission basis without providing the travel services sold, see 63204
•provision of homes and furnished or unfurnished flats or apartments for more permanent use, typically on a monthly or annual basis, see 68102
•combination of day-to-day administrative services to non-related enterprises, see 82110
Class Title: Short Term Accommodation Activities

SSIC 2020 Title: Hostels and dormitories for students, workers and other individuals
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the provision of temporary or longer-term accommodation in single or shared rooms or dormitories for students, workers and other individuals. 

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•student residences
•school dormitories
•worker hostels
•lodging and boarding houses
Cross References: •short term accommodation activities like backpackers/travellers’ hostels, guesthouses, capsule hotel, etc., see 55103
Group Title: HOSTELS AND DORMITORIES FOR STUDENTS, WORKERS AND OTHER INDIVIDUALS
Class Title: Hostels and dormitories for students, workers and other individuals

SSIC 2020 Title: Fast food outlets
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class refers to:
•limited service restaurants that sell cooked fast food which is typically consumed as a meal or part of a meal and can be prepared and served quickly upon order
- the food sold is usually designed to be eaten on the go and mostly does not require the use of cutlery to be consumed
- the food may be for immediate consumption, take out or delivery.
- customers mostly serve themselves using a tray over a counter and are required to pay before receiving the food
Cross References:

SSIC 2020 Title: Stalls selling cooked food and prepared drinks (including stalls at food courts and mobile food hawkers)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes activities of hawkers and stall-holders selling cooked food and prepared drinks from stalls at food courts, coffee shops and canteens or mobile vehicles for immediate consumption.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•activities of:
- hawkers and stall-holders selling cooked food
- hawkers and stall-holders selling prepared drinks
- mobile food hawkers (e.g. mobile ice cream vendor, night market stall holder)
- pushcarts selling cooked food or prepared drinks

SSIC 2020 Title: Food caterers
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the provision of food services based on contractual arrangements with the customer, at the location specified by the customer, for a specific event or for a specific period of time based on a menu specified by the customer. The food is often prepared in a central unit.

Meals and snacks may be transported and/or prepared and served on or off the premises, as required by the customer.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
- event catering
- transportation catering (e.g. airline catering)
- home meal catering for a specific period of time
Cross References:
•operation of canteens, see 56122
•online marketplaces for goods (including food), see 63201
•online intermediaries that enable transactions between buyers and sellers usually for a fee or commission basis without preparing the food sold, see 63201
Class Title: Food Caterers

SSIC 2020 Title: Publishing of books, brochures, musical books and other publications
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the publishing of the following: 
•books, brochures, leaflets
•dictionaries, encyclopedias, textbooks and educational materials
•atlases, maps and charts 
•music and sheet books

Units in this Sub-class make copyrighted content available to the general public by engaging in the reproduction and distribution of this content in various forms (e.g. print, electronic or audio form, on the Internet).
Cross References:
•production of globes, see 32909
•publishing of advertising material (e.g. brochures), see 58190
•publishing of blogs, see 58190

Class Title: Book Publishing

SSIC 2020 Title: Publishing of directories and mailing lists (including financial databases)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the publishing of lists of facts/information (databases) that are protected in their form, but not in their content.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged one or more of the following:
•publishing of mailing lists
•publishing of telephone books
•publishing of statistics databases
•publishing of financial databases
•publishing of other directories and compilations, such as case law, pharmaceutical compendia, etc.

Units in this Sub-class make copyrighted content available to the general public by engaging in the reproduction and distribution of this content in various forms (e.g. print, electronic or audio form, on the Internet).

SSIC 2020 Title: Sound recording production
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the provision of facilities and technical expertise for sound recording in a studio. Audio production and post-production services are provided to produce master recordings and the audio services provided can be for film, television and video productions.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in:
•production of original (sound) master recordings, such as tapes, CDs
•sound recording service activities in a studio or elsewhere, including the production of taped (i.e. non-live) radio programming, audio for film, television, etc.
Cross References:
•reproduction from master copies of music or other sound recordings, see 18200
•radio broadcasting stations, see 60100
•wholesale of recorded audio tapes and disks, see 46442
•music publishing and distribution activities , see 59202

SSIC 2020 Title: Music publishing and distribution activities
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes music publishing activities in various forms (e.g. disc, electronic form). Units engaged in these activities may own the copyright or act as administrator of the music copyrights on behalf of the copyright owners.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following activities:
•acquiring and registering copyrights for musical compositions
•promoting, authorising and using these compositions in recordings, radio, television, movies, live performances, print and other media
•distributing sound recordings to wholesalers, retailers or directly to the public
Cross References:
•reproduction from master copies of music or other sound recordings, see 18200
•wholesale of recorded audio tapes and disks, see 46442

SSIC 2020 Title: Radio programme production and broadcasting
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the activities of creating radio content on entertainment, news, talk, and the like or acquiring the right to distribute these content and subsequently broadcasting these content. Also included is data broadcasting, typically integrated with radio broadcasting. The broadcasting can be performed using different technologies, over-the-air, via satellite, via a cable network or via Internet. The production of radio programmes that are typically narrowcast in nature (limited format, such as news, sports, education or youth-oriented programming) on a subscription or fee basis, to a third party, for subsequent broadcasting to the public is also included. 

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following: 
•broadcasting audio signals through radio broadcasting studios and facilities for the transmission of aural programming to the public, to affiliates or to subscribers. The aural programmes may originate in their own radio studios, from an affiliated network or from external sources
•activities of radio networks, i.e. assembling and transmitting aural programming to the affiliates or subscribers via over-the-air broadcasts, cable or satellite
•broadcasting activities over the Internet (Internet radio stations)
•data broadcasting integrated with radio broadcasting.
Cross References: •production of taped radio programming, see 59201
Class Title: Radio Programme Production and Broadcasting

SSIC 2020 Title: Television programming and broadcasting (including cable, satellite, terrestrial television, internet and mobile)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the activities of creating television content on entertainment, news, talk, and the like or acquiring the right to distribute these content and subsequently broadcasting these content. The complete television programme can be either broadcast by the producing unit or produced for transmission by third party distributors, such as cable companies or satellite television providers. The programming may be of a general or specialised nature (e.g. limited formats such as news, sports, education or youth oriented programming), may be made freely available to users or may be available only on a subscription basis. Also included is data broadcasting, typically integrated with television broadcasting. The broadcasting can be performed using different technologies, over-the-air, via satellite, via a cable network or via Internet. 

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•creation of a complete television channel programme, from purchased programme components (e.g. movies, documentaries), self-produced programme components (e.g. local news, live reports) or a combination thereof
•programming of video-on-demand channels
•data broadcasting integrated with television broadcasting
•video streaming via internet
Cross References:
•production of television programme elements (e.g. movies, documentaries,  commercials), see 5911
•provision of non-data centre hosting services for streaming services, see 63111
•provision of data centre hosting services for streaming services, see 63112
Class Title: Television Programming and Broadcasting

SSIC 2020 Title: Wired telecommunications network operation (including fixed-line, fibre optics, local/international PSTN and leased circuits)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes:
•operating, maintaining or providing access to facilities for the transmission of voice, data, text, sound and video using wired telecommunications infrastructure, including:
- operating and maintaining switching and transmission facilities to provide point-to-point communications via landlines, microwave or a combination of landlines and satellite linkups
- operating of cable distribution systems (e.g. for distribution of data and television signals)
- furnishing telegraph and other non-vocal communications using own facilities
•purchasing access and network capacity from owners and operators of networks and providing telecommunications services using this capacity to businesses and households
•fixed lines services (including local/international PSTN and leased circuit)

The transmission facilities that carry out these activities, may be based on a single technology or a combination of technologies.
Cross References:
•telecommunications resellers and internet access providers, see 6109
•mobile cellular and other wireless telecommunications network operation , see 61012
•satellite telecommunications network operation, see 61013
Class Title: Telecommunications Network Operation

SSIC 2020 Title: Mobile cellular and other wireless telecommunications network operation
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes:
•operating, maintaining or providing access to facilities for the transmission of voice, data, text, sound, and video using wireless telecommunications infrastructure
•maintaining and operating mobile cellular and other wireless telecommunications networks
•purchasing access and network capacity from owners and operators of networks and providing wireless telecommunications services (except satellite) using this capacity to businesses and households
The transmission facilities provide omni-directional transmission via airwaves and may be based on a single technology or a combination of technologies.
Cross References:
•wired telecommunications network operation (including fixed-line, fibre optics, local/international PSTN and leased circuits), see 61011
•satellite telecommunications network operation, see 61013
•telecommunications resellers and internet access providers, see 6109

SSIC 2020 Title: Satellite telecommunications network operation

•delivery of visual, aural or textual programming received from cable networks, local television stations or radio networks to consumers via direct-to-home satellite systems (The units classified here do not generally originate programming material.)
•purchasing access and network capacity from owners and operators of networks and providing telecommunications services using this capacity to businesses and households
Cross References:
•wired telecommunications network operation (including fixed-line, fibre optics, local/international PSTN and leased circuits), see 61011

•operation of Business-to-Consumer (B2C) and Business-to-Business (B2B) online marketplaces for goods (including food) on a fee or commission basis
•operation of Consumer-to-Consumer (C2C) online marketplaces for cooked food

Online marketplaces are intermediary platforms that enable transactions between buyers and sellers usually for a fee or on a commission basis. The online marketplaces facilitate the orders for goods and cooked food sold through their platforms, without preparing the cooked food or taking ownership of the goods sold.

Units in this Sub-class may not:

•deal in any foreign currency, gold or other precious metals or acquire foreign currency denominated stocks, shares or debt securities

The portfolios are customised to achieve specific investment characteristics, such as diversification, risk, rate of return and price volatility. These entities earn interest, dividends and other property income, but have little or no employment and no revenue from the sale of services.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:

SSIC 2020 Title: Financial leasing companies
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes leasing where the term approximately covers the expected life of the asset and the lessee acquires substantially all the benefits of its use and takes all the risks associated with its ownership. Such leases cover all or virtually all costs including interest.

Finance leasing differs from rental business in that units engaged in rental business keep stock of and take title to the goods they rent. However, units engaged in finance leasing do not keep stock of the goods they leased. Instead, they finance their clients in the purchase of machinery or equipment from outlets of clients' choice. The finance leasing companies (lessor) maintains ownership of the asset. After the terms of leasing expire, the ownership of the goods may or may not be transferred to the clients (lessee).
Cross References: •operational leasing, see Division 77, according to type of goods leased

SSIC 2020 Title: Life insurance
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the underwriting of annuities and life insurance policies and investing premiums to build a portfolio of financial assets to be used against future claims.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following: 
•underwriting and provision of:
- annuities and life insurance policies
- disability income insurance policies
- accidental death and dismemberment insurance policies (with or without substantial savings element)

SSIC 2020 Title: Legal activities (excluding online marketplaces)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes legal advice, representation and related legal services by, or under supervision of, persons who are members of the bar as part of legal procedure in courts or other judicial bodies.

Units in this Sub-class are engaged in one or more of the following: 
•advice, representation and related legal services in all areas of law (e.g. criminal law, civil law, administrative law, labour disputes, and arbitration and mediation as part of legal procedure)
•provision of general legal counsel and/or legal advice and other related legal services
•preparation and/or certification of legal documents (e.g. articles of incorporation, partnership agreements or similar documents in connection with company formation, patents, trade marks and copyrights, preparation of deeds, wills, trusts, etc.) and other related legal services
•other activities of notaries public, civil law notaries, bailiffs, arbitrators and mediators, examiners and referees
Cross References:
•online marketplaces for legal, arbitration and mediation services, see 63209
•online intermediaries that enable transactions between buyers and sellers usually for a fee or commission basis without providing the legal, arbitration and mediation services, see 63209
•arbitration and mediation services provided by quasi-judicial or non-judicial bodies, see 69102
•representative office set up by law practice, see 70102
•corporate immigration consultancy, see 7020
•brokerage and consultancy services of intellectual property assets by non-legal firms, see 74902 
•arbitration and mediation services provided by courts or other judicial bodies, see 84231 
•administration and operation of civil and criminal law courts, military tribunals and the judicial system, see 84231
Class Title: Legal Activities

SSIC 2020 Title: Accounting and auditing services (excluding online marketplaces)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes accounting and auditing services.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•preparation of management accounting reports
•preparation or auditing of financial accounts
•examination of accounts and certification of their accuracy
•preparation of personal and business income tax returns
•advisory activities and representation on behalf of clients before tax authorities
•advisory services relating to audit and assurance
•accounting advisory and consultancy services (e.g. business valuation)
•business assurance services such as internal audit, restructuring and/or insolvency, risk management and/or governance and corporate finance and/or deal advisory

SSIC 2020 Title: General building engineering design and consultancy services
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes :
•general building engineering design (i.e. applying physical laws and principles of engineering in the engineering project). Other services related to the engineering project may be provided as well, for example: provision of advice regarding engineering principles and methods, preparation of feasibility studies, preparation of preliminary and final plans and designs, provision of technical services during the construction or installation phase, inspection and evaluation of the project.
•general building engineering technical consultancy services (i.e. provision of advice to clients regarding engineering principles and methods), like building diagnostic and inspection services (i.e. evaluate all aspects of the building structure and component systems and prepare a report on the physical condition of the property)
•general building engineering project development and management
Cross References:
•building construction services, see 4100
•architectural services (i.e. planning and designing residential, institutional, leisure, commercial, and industrial buildings and structures by applying knowledge of design, construction procedures, building codes, and building material), see 71111

•environmental engineering design and consultancy services (except clean energy), see 71124
•infrastructure engineering design and consultancy services , see 71125
•engineering design and consultancy services supporting mining, oil and gas extraction and offshore exploration activities , see 71126
•technical testing (including certification of products and services), see 71200
•research and experimental development activities related to engineering, see 72104 
•industrial design (i.e. creating and developing designs and specifications that optimise the use, value and appearance of products), see 7411
•interior design services, see 74191

SSIC 2020 Title: Technical testing and analysis services (including certification of products and services)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes testing of performance of physical, chemical and other analytical testing of all types of materials and products such as:
•testing of composition and purity of minerals, etc.
•testing activities in the field of food hygiene, including veterinary testing and control in relation to food production
•testing of physical characteristics and performance of materials, such as strength, thickness, durability, radioactivity
•performance testing of complete machinery, such as motors, automobiles, electronic equipment
•radiographic testing of welds and joints testing and measuring of environmental indicators, such as air and water pollution
•bunker surveying which involves providing inspections and examinations of the fuel for marine vessels and bunkers, such as fuel sampling 
•preparations, checking presence of water in fuel, measurements of oil fuel temperature
•activities of certification and accreditation of products and services
Cross References:
•clinical testing, see 72106
•testing of animal specimens, see 75000
•testing and analysis of medical and dental specimens, see 86901

Detailed Definitions: This Sub-class includes biotechnology research and experimental development (R&D) that involves the study of the use of microorganisms and cellular and biomolecular processes to develop or alter living or non-living materials. This research and development in biotechnology may result in development of new processes or in prototypes of new products that may be reproduced, utilised, or implemented by various industries (excluding medical science).

SSIC 2020 Title: Advertising activities
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes establishments involved in planning, creating and executing public relations, marketing and branding campaigns across digital and non-digital channels. 

These includes the provision of: 
•advertising and creative services, such as conceptualisation and production of commercial advertisements through various channels like radio, television, outdoor, social media, electronic mailers, etc.
•planning and conducting of integrated marketing strategies via, for example, marketing-specific competitive and customer analyses to inform on target customer segments, competitive positioning and price determination
•media selection, buying and placement services 
•media and stakeholder engagements
Cross References:
•production of commercial messages for radio, television and film, see SSIC 59112
•provision of advice and guidance on projects relating to public relations, marketing and branding without conducting campaigns, see SSIC 70205
•market research, see SSIC 73200

•mailing support activities, see SSIC 82199 
•convention and trade show organisers, see SSIC 82302
•art and graphic design activities without conducting advertising campaigns, see SSIC 74192

SSIC 2020 Title: Market research and public opinion polling

SSIC 2020 Title: Leasing of non-financial intangible assets (e.g. patents, trade marks, brand names etc)
Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes the activities of allowing others to use intellectual property products and similar products for which a royalty payment or licensing fee is paid to the owner of the product (i.e. the asset holder). The leasing of these products can take various forms, such as permission for reproduction, use in subsequent processes or products, operating businesses under a franchise. The current owners may or may not have created these products.

Units in this Sub-class are primarily engaged in one or more of the following:
•leasing of intellectual property products (except copyrighted works, such as books or software)
•receiving royalties or licensing fees for the use of:
- trade marks or service marks
- brand names
- franchise agreements
Cross References:
•online marketplaces for rental and leasing of goods, see 63209
•leasing of real estate, see 6810 
•leasing of tangible products (assets), see 771 to 773 
•acquisition of rights and publishing, see Divisions 58 and 59
•producing, reproducing and distributing copyrighted works (books, software, film), see Divisions 58, 59
Class Title: Leasing of Non-Financial Intangible Assets

- conveyance
- both conveyance and accommodation
- visits to places or points of interest, including but not limited to historical sites, cultural precincts or attractions

Some of the services provided by these firms include itinerary planning and guided tours.

SSIC 2020 Title: Landscape planting, care and maintenance service activities (e.g. garden installation and maintenance, grass cutting, tree felling, pruning)

- public and private housing

- protection against noise, wind, erosion

SSIC 2020 Title: Nurseries and kindergartens
Detailed Definitions: This Sub-class includes nurseries and kindergartens. Pre-primary education is defined as the initial stage of organised instruction designed primarily to introduce very young children to a school-type environment, that is, to provide a bridge between the home and a school-based atmosphere.
Cross References:
•child day-care activities, see 88911
•international and foreign system schools, see 85230
•schools for students with special needs, see 85240
•academic tutoring services (e.g. tuition centres, private tutoring services), see 85409

SSIC 2020 Title: Primary schools
Detailed Definitions: This Sub-class includes primary schools. These education courses aim to give students a sound basic education in reading, writing and mathematics and an elementary understanding of other subjects such as history, geography, natural science, social science, art and music. Such education is generally provided for children, however the provision of literacy programmes within or outside the school system, which are similar in content to programmes in primary education but are intended for those considered too old to enter elementary schools, is also included (i.e. adult literacy programmes).
Cross References:
•child day-care activities, see 88911
•international and foreign system schools, see 85230
•schools for students with special needs, see 85240
•academic tutoring services (e.g. tuition centres, private tutoring services), see 85409
Class Title: Pre-Primary and Primary Education

Detailed Definitions:
This Sub-class includes:
•the provision of education service at the secondary level, giving access to post-secondary (non-tertiary) or higher education. Such units provide programmes that are usually on a more subject-oriented pattern using more specialised teachers, and more often employ several teachers conducting classes in their field of specialisation. 
•education can be provided through various channels (e.g. classrooms, Internet, at home)
•programmes at this level are usually designated to qualify students either for post-secondary (non-tertiary) education or higher education
Cross References:
•junior colleges and centralised pre-university institutes (post-secondary non-tertiary) including combined secondary schools and post-secondary non-tertiary schools, see 85212
•international and foreign system schools, see 85230
•schools for students with special educational needs, see 85240
•commercial schools offering general secondary and post-secondary non-tertiary education programmes, see 85213
•academic tutoring services (e.g. tuition centres, private tutoring services), see 85409

SSIC 2020 Title: Activities of households as employers of domestic workers

This Sub-class includes activities of households as employers of maids.
